column7: We Nearly Scrapped This Video Idea
column9:
Hey Candace,

Quick thing before we start, weve just released a major new
update on Voicepal (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/v8ukg7rvwltrhvve4v8tghv4kelllf9/kkhmh2ung2ee5luk/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2NyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcy8yNQ==
), the AI writing app that me and my team are developing,
including a highly requested feature, stats, so now you can see
just how many words you've written with the help of the app.
We've had a lot of positive feedback about it from creators so
thought Id mention it in case you're interested. You can try it
for free on iOS and Android - here's a link (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/v8ukg7rvwltrhvve4v8tghv4kelllf9/kkhmh2ung2ee5luk/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2NyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcy8yNQ==
).

Right, on with todays email which is the second part of my spiel
on packaging and this is a long email so settle in 

Last week, I shared our new system for optimising the titles and
thumbnails of our YouTube videos.

Today - as promised - Ill give you a behind the scenes look at
how we landed on the title for a video we released last month -
Stop Wasting Time - How to Change your Life in 90 Days - and the
unconventional way that we arrived on the final thumbnail.

Im hoping itll be useful to see exactly how we package one of
our YouTube videos from start to finish (and beyond).

 Step 1 - Banking Ideas
------------------------

The idea for this video was actually first added into our Notion
database back in May last year - 8 months before it was finally
released.

Over the course of several months, ideas and notes were added to
our Notion card but it wasnt until October that it got brought
into the main production pipeline.

And this isnt unusual for us. In fact, this is a good example of
a process I talk about in PTYA called slow burns - its the
idea that not every video has to be created from an idea that you
had last week. Of course, there will be some videos where that
does happen but you should also give space to those ideas that
you know instinctively will make for a good video but youre not
quite sure what the right framing or structure should be - thats
where the idea of slow burns comes in.

(On this point, Notions Version History feature is really useful
when were looking back through changes that weve made on some
of these slow burns ).

Anyway, this was originally going to be a video titled something
like How to Turn Your Life Around in 6-12 Months but over time
the plan changed and the title was refined to align more with my
concept of Quarterly Quests which is something I've developed as
part of my productivity system, LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/v8ukg7rvwltrhvve4v8tghv4kelllf9/qvh8h8udg2vv4nhg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249cGFja2FnaW5nX3B0MiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3JlYXRvcm5vdGVz
).

So by the time we began talking about the video in one of our
brainstorming meetings, wed refined things down to 'how to
completely change your life in 90 days'.

 Step 2 - The Rating Metric
----------------------------

Youll probably remember our star system from my last email,
where we rate video ideas based on how many views we think
theyll each get in the first 24 hours 

And the rating for this one across the team present in the
meeting was about 3 stars (a prediction of 75-100k views in the
first day of it being live on the channel), which is ok - but
definitely not great.

In short, we thought the concept was good but we needed to refine
the packaging to improve its chances of performing well.

 Step 3 - Finalising the Title
-------------------------------

One of the main problems with this original title was that it
wasnt quite going to stand out in the sea of other videos being
released in the New Year period.

How to completely change your life in 90 days was a bit too
generic, especially being released slightly later in the month.
We needed the title to be a bit more compelling, make a bit more
of a statement and address a key audience pain point - that
feeling of wasting time.

So we came up with a bunch of different title variations,
including things like:

* You dont need a year to change your life: The Quest Method
* How to change your life in 90 days: The Quarterly Quest Method
* Change your Life in 90 Days: The Quarterly Quest Method
* Stop Wasting Time - How to Change your Life in 90 Days
* How to Change your Life - The 12-Week Transformation
* Youre Not Behind: How to Change Your Life in 90 Days
* How to become Unrecognisable in 90 days
* How to Change your Life in Just 12 Weeks

(Tip - We always try to make sure our titles are 52 characters or
less, otherwise YouTube will cut off the last part and this it
makes it hard for viewers to see exactly what the video is
about.)

Youll notice many of these ideas feature Quarterly Quest or
Quarterly Quest Method and thats because we know that applying
frameworks to these videos and calling them out in the title has
historically performed well for us so we were tempted to run with
the Quest Method.





Obviously, you dont want to fall into the trap of repeating
content, overusing certain titles, or overusing frameworks but
historical performance of videos can be a useful guide.

In the end though, we settled on a different, more direct
approach and published the video with the title Stop Wasting
Time - How to Change your Life in 90 Days.

(Feel free to hit reply and tell me if youd have gone with
something else )

 Step 4 - Brainstorming Thumbnail Ideas
----------------------------------------

The last part of our discussion was all about the thumbnail - the
other most important element of a videos packaging.

We did have a few variations already mocked up based on things
that had worked previously that included my face / photos of me
but my team and I are really keen on experimenting with faceless
thumbnails at the moment, as Ive mentioned before in these
emails, so we wanted to try something a bit different.

We know that the overhead angle tends to work quite nicely for us
(see above ) but we werent quite sure how to visualise that 90
day element in an effective way.

But then my General Manager, Angus, remembered a random
screenshot hed taken on January 1st of the calendar app on this
phone and suggested we could use that as inspiration given that
we were releasing this in January.

And that became the first iteration (below left).

The problem with this first version was that it felt too much
like an ad. There was no surrounding context, plus the dark mode
didnt really fit with the brand.

So that led to us pivoting towards a lightmode version placed on
an iPad on my desk, which is still the primary thumbnail being
used to this day.

This was perhaps one of the most unconventional means of getting
to the end result but its often in the random parts of everyday
life that you can find inspiration and this certainly seemed to
strike a chord as the video was a 1 out of 10 when it was first
released 





 Step 5: A/B Testing
---------------------

The final part is the testing stage post-publication and, if you
look at the video now, youll notice that weve already made a
change to the title based on an A/B test result.

The current title Youre Not Behind: How to Change Your Life in
90 Days marginally outperformed the initial version in our test
so weve switched things up for now. (The result was marginal
though so we might run this test again at some point).

The next stage is testing the thumbnail and were actually
planning on running that test this week so if youre reading this
on Thursday or Friday, you might be seeing a different thumbnail.

Were essentially going to be stress-testing the hypothesis of
faceless vs my face. Honestly, weve had mixed results on these
tests in the past and weve generally found that it really does
depend on the video topic but Ill let you know how things go.

(Note: for all our testing we use Thumbnail Test (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/v8ukg7rvwltrhvve4v8tghv4kelllf9/wnh2h6uq9v44kpil/aHR0cHM6Ly90aHVtYm5haWx0ZXN0LmNvbS8=
) - YouTube does have its own feature but its pretty reductive
in the data that it shares but you can get way more data points
from Thumbnail Test).

Right, that was a long email 

Hopefully this was somewhat useful in giving you a little behind
the scenes look into what were doing - do let me know if youd
like to see more of this style of content.

Right now, my team and I are working hard on optimising our
packaging process, and it definitely helps when were all able to
share our different thoughts and perspective on one big Zoom
call.

And if youd like to experience that kind of community and
collaborative feel - where you can exchange feedback and ideas
with others - Id love for you to join us over in the Part-Time
YouTuber Academy (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/v8ukg7rvwltrhvve4v8tghv4kelllf9/m2h7h6u3k099qrbl/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXBhY2thZ2luZ19wdDImdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
). Wed love to have you 

Thats all for now - heres to making some epic videos in 2025 :)

Ali xx

 Want to start a YouTube channel? Go here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/v8ukg7rvwltrhvve4v8tghv4kelllf9/p8hehqu4k5dddlcr/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5wdHlhLmNvbS9wdHlhLWJsLWZvb3Rlcg==
).

Unsubscribe from PTYA updates (

) |
Unsubscribe from all email updates (
https://unsubscribe.convertkit-mail2.com/v8ukg7rvwltrhvve4v8tghv4kelllf9
) |
Update your email preferences (

column7: 7 Questions Every Data Team Should Ask the Business
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/7-questions-every-data-team-should

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders; Ben here 
Before diving into todays newsletter, I want to take a moment to thank this issues sponsor, BMC [ https://substack.com/redirect/79e1cad7-f325-49f6-b1d0-d297151b4a0e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. Many data teams still spend too much time babysitting pipelines and stitching together scripts. Control-M helps automate that work, coordinating data workflows, triggering ML jobs, and syncing across cloud platforms, so teams can focus on analysis instead of maintenance.
Check out their latest case study to see how it can simplify complex workflows [ https://substack.com/redirect/9647d9d7-45d3-4bf1-9bc0-e6b07c422321?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Now lets jump into the article!
A common challenge for data teams is figuring out what to work on that will drive the most value.
In some cases, the business has projects they believe should be taken on that you might disagree with, but you dont have a solid list of suggestions, so youre stuck with what theyve asked you to work on.
In other cases, the business team might not know exactly how theyd like to use data, other than perhaps a dashboard or two. That means you cant just ask, What data projects do you need? and expect a helpful answer.
Instead, you need to ask questions that uncover pain points, opportunities, and processes where data could make a meaningful difference.
At Facebook, we conducted this exercise every six months to realign priorities and identify new, high-impact projects. Wed go and talk to our business partners to understand their current and future needs. From there, wed work to come up with projects we believed aligned.
If you are looking for questions to help you better align with the business, here are seven questions you can ask to surface valuable data. (Also, Id love to hear if you have any questions youd recommend.)
1) Whats keeping your team from hitting its targets right now?
Not everything is about data. Many leaders recognize that there may be areas where they are struggling to meet targets.
Perhaps they arent converting enough on ads, or their team has consistently missed the mark when it comes to delivering products on time. There are real-life situations where data may or may not be helpful.
But instead of asking, Where can data help, your focus should be on understanding the bigger picture.
Department Specific Versions Of This Question
Finance - Are there recurring surprises in expenses or revenue that you wish you could predict earlier?
Marketing - Are there channels where you feel youre spending too much but not seeing results?
Operations - Where do delays or inefficiencies tend to pop up in your daily workflow?
2) If I could give you insight to metric A and it went up or down 20% what would you do?
This is a question I ask as a follow-up to the question: What key metrics are your team responsible for over the next half, and which ones do you not have access to that you wish you did? Once they answer, my next question is posed as a way of taking the leader through a thought experiment.
Lets say you do have insight into this metric, and it does change.
So what?
Can you do anything about it? Have you even thought that far? Some business leaders seriously havent.
Department Specific Versions Of This Question
Finance -If your cash flow projection changed by 20%, what levers would you pull?
Marketing - If organic conversions dropped 20%, how would that change your strategy?
Product - If churn went down 20%, what would you double down on?
3)When was the last time a data insight changed your plan or decision?
This question is somewhat of an are you a believer question. Everyone likes to say they are data-driven, but if you ask someone this question and they dont have an answer, this should cause you to pause.
My follow-up question would be something along the lines of Why not?
This could lead them to say something along the lines of I dont trust the data, or perhaps they simply rely on their intuition.
On one hand, you might need to address the data quality issue if it is a legitimate concern. On the other hand, this stakeholder might not be the right one for you to take a project from.
Department Specific Versions Of This Question
Finance - When did a forecast or variance analysis cause you to change your spending plan?
Marketing - Did any A/B test results surprise you recently?
Product - Did data ever contradict what user feedback suggested?
4)Where are we spending a lot of effort without seeing results?
Many business teams have established workflows that they must follow. Finance and accounting teams must close the books every month, while other teams may need to make partner payments and utilize a CSV-heavy process to calculate them. Additionally, there are numerous board reports and other tasks to attend to.
An alternative question could be - Whats something that feels manual or time-consuming in your process?
Department Specific Versions Of This Question
Finance - Which recurring reports take time to create but dont seem to influence decisions?
Marketing - Which campaigns require heavy effort but dont convert well?
5) Who are the key stakeholders you report to, and what metrics do they care about most?
I really enjoyed my conversation with Celina Wong [ https://substack.com/redirect/8472a3c9-3059-42a2-ad47-d1d74988c898?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] a few months back. One of the points she brought up is that often, we deliver metrics, reports, and analyses that dont stop with our stakeholders.
They are heading to the next stakeholder(often in a more condensed manner). Ive had multiple conversations where the leader on the other side said something along the lines of, I can sell that to the CEO or I just need a clear narrative to tell the board.
Our work as data teams is going somewhere, so we might as well know where.
Department Specific Versions Of This Question
Finance - What metrics does the CFO or board scrutinize every quarter?
Marketing - What story do you have to tell in your quarterly review?
Product - How do you summarize product impact for leadership?
SeattleDataGuys Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
6) What win in the last 3-6 months are you looking to double down on?
I enjoy giving my business partners space to share with me the wins they are most proud of. One, I like knowing what drives other partners, but it could also show where there might be an opportunity for the data team to amplify a recent win.
Department Specific Versions Of This Question
Marketing - Which campaign or audience segment performed better than expected?
Product: - Which recent feature exceeded expectations, what might be driving that?
7) When was the last time you made a bad (or late) decision because you lacked the right data?
This question provides several benefits. First, it allows you insight into how a business leader thinks about data. Have they thought through where data might have been helpful in making a decision in the past?
In some cases, this question might get you a very empty answer, where the business leader might not really say anything because they have never really used data anyway.
In other cases, there might be very clear pain points that you elicit by asking this question. Where the business leader will be like Why yes, in fact, two weeks ago I was trying to decide on how to spend marketing dollars
If they do say Two weeks ago, Id push back on that and see if that was merely recency bias. But overall, its a great question to start digging even deeper.
Department Specific Versions Of This Question
Finance: - When did missing or delayed data make it hard to forecast or budget accurately?
Marketing - When did you launch or pause a campaign without knowing how it was performing?
Product - When did a lack of user or performance data delay a product launch or decision?
Final Thoughts
When you ask, What do you need from data? youre really asking them to think like you. And that limits what theyll say, because they can only imagine the solutions they already know exist.
If you flip it, and start from their perspective , their pain points, their decisions, their blind spots, youll uncover work that actually changes how the business runs.
As always, thanks for reading.
Upcoming Data Events
Seattle Happy Hour At The Rhein Haus With BMC [ https://substack.com/redirect/fd95bc97-bcd8-4339-9604-60116aca411b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ](Ill Be There!)
Airflow Summit 2025(Ill be there!) [ https://substack.com/redirect/bdb8655a-aac0-4f2b-bc94-bf6084ce9e73?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Streaming Kafka Data into MotherDuck with Estuary Flow [ https://substack.com/redirect/a68daebd-4db3-4480-81c7-a08249ccc469?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
How To Turn Around A Failing Data Team
A few years ago, I heard the same observation from several data and business leaders.
The default state of data teams is failure.
This was in the early 2020s, when many data teams felt like they had ballooned in size. Everyone wanted to be data-driven and cheap money made it easy.
Fast-forward to 2025 and the landscape looks very different. Companies are running leaner. Many have intentionally shrunk their data teams and, in some cases, lean more on external partners instead of adding headcount.
As a consultant, Im often brought in when a previous team has disbanded or when leadership wants to turn around a struggling data environment. Across these engagements, Ive seen recurring patterns, root causes that explain why some data stacks and teams fail to deliver, and what it really takes to bring them back on track.

But thats not how it works Candace.



Coaching is NOT mentoring...



(The two get mixed up a lot).



You DONT need to be more successful than your coaching clients to help them.



Especially not for life coaching. ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/ovsl-video-bau-e/?el=OVSL-email-one-myth-156-1&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+156-1&utm_content_name=%231+myth+about+coaching&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )



Life coaches are there to motivate and push clients forward towards their life goals.



And guide them to find the answers they need within the knowledge they already have.



Its about empowering people to use more of the skills they already have.



And building their confidence, by offering emotional support.



Once you understand the principles



Life coaching can be applied to ANY area of life:



 Career



 Family



 Relationships



 Health



 Personal well-being



If you want to learn those empowering principles from me and my team of world-class life coaches, between now and July



So you can use them to help yourself (and others) achieve life-changing goals
